What: Using order_item_id as a uniqueness indicator is not sufficient to detect duplicates.
  - A line-item timestamp (or other meaningful business attribute) should be used to enforce uniqueness and detect true duplicates.
  - This ensures data integrity and avoids false positives in reporting and audits.

What: The Issue with order_item_id as the sole uniqueness indicator

      | order_id | order_item_id | product_id | price |
      | -------- | ------------- | ---------- | ----- |
      | ORD_001  | ITEM_001      | PROD_001   | 3000  |
      | ORD_001  | ITEM_002      | PROD_001   | 3000  |

If you only rely on order_item_id:
  - Both rows are technically unique
  - But from a business perspective, they might actually be duplicates (same product, same price)
  - order_item_id creates a false positive, making it look like everything is fine when you may have an issue
